Package neureka.backend.api.algorithms

Class AbstractFunctionalAlgorithm<FinalType extends Algorithm<FinalType>>

java.lang.Object
neureka.backend.api.algorithms.AbstractBaseAlgorithm<FinalType>
neureka.backend.api.algorithms.AbstractFunctionalAlgorithm<FinalType>
Type Parameters:
FinalType - The final type extending this class.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Algorithm<FinalType>
Direct Known Subclasses:
Activation, Broadcast, Convolution, GenericAlgorithm, Operator, Scalarization
public abstract class AbstractFunctionalAlgorithm<FinalType extends Algorithm<FinalType>>
extends AbstractBaseAlgorithm<FinalType>
This is the base class for implementations of the Algorithm interface. The class implements a basic component system, as is implicitly expected by said interface. Additionally it contains useful methods used to process passed arguments of ExecutionCall as well as an implementation of the Algorithm interface which allows its methods to be implemented in a functional programming style, meaning that instances of concrete implementations extending this abstract class have setters for lambdas representing the Algorithm methods. It is being used by the standard backend of Neureka as abstract base class for various algorithms. Conceptually an implementation of the Algorithm interface represents "a sub-kind of operation" for an instance of an implementation of the Operation interface.
The "+" operator for example has different Algorithm instances tailored to specific requirements originating from different ExecutionCall instances with unique arguments. Tsr instances within an execution call having the same shape would cause the Operation instance to chose an Algorithm instance which is responsible for performing elementwise operations, whereas otherwise the Broadcast algorithm might be called to perform the operation.

    • getHandleInsteadOfDevice

      public Algorithm.InitialCallHook getHandleInsteadOfDevice()
      The Algorithm.InitialCallHook lambda is simply a bypass procedure which if provided will simply occupy the rest of the execution without any other steps being taken. For example the Algorithm.RecursiveJunctor would not be used in that case. This bypassing is useful for unorthodox types of operations like the Reshape opertion.
      Returns:
      A lambda which bypasses the default execution procedure.

    • getHandleRecursivelyAccordingToArity

      public Algorithm.RecursiveJunctor getHandleRecursivelyAccordingToArity()
      This returns an instance of the Algorithm.RecursiveJunctor which enables the pairwise execution of a chain of an abitrary number of ExecutionCall arguments. This is useful for simple operators like '+' or '*' which might have any number of arguments...
      Returns:
      A lambda which will be executed recursively to executes multiple arguments pairwise.
